      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kinda yellow and pale compared to the top ones. what's probably going on with them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves on tomato plants can be a bit of a mystery, but I think I can help you narrow it down. It's possible that your plants are experiencing a bit of a \"garden goblin\" problem, where the lower leaves are getting too much shade, causing them to turn yellow and pale. This is especially common when the plants are top-heavy with fruit, like tomatoes, and the lower leaves are getting blocked by the weight of the fruit. It's a bit like when a group of rowdy kids in a small room can't help but get a bit rowdy, and the lower leaves are getting overwhelmed by the shade. \n\nAnother possibility is that your plants are experiencing a nutrient deficiency, which can cause the lower leaves to turn yellow. This is often due to a lack of magnesium or potassium, which are essential nutrients for plant growth. But don't worry, it's an easy fix! Just make sure to fertilize your plants regularly, and they should be back to their old self in no time. \n\nIt's also worth noting that tomato plants can be prone to a condition called \"lower leaf scorch,\" which is caused by a lack of water or extreme temperatures. But if you're providing your plants with plenty",
