      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, garden goblin? What do you mean by that? I didn't mention any pests or anything, just the yellow leaves. And you mentioned magnesium or potassium, how do I actually check if that's the problem? I'm not sure what to do next.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I must have gotten a bit carried away with the whole \"garden goblin\" thing. I was just trying to come up with a creative explanation, but I see how it might have been confusing. Let's focus on the actual issue at hand.\n\nTo check for magnesium or potassium deficiencies, you can perform a simple soil test. You can buy a DIY soil test kit at most gardening stores, or you can send a sample to a lab for analysis. The kit will typically involve collecting a small sample of soil and sending it to a lab for analysis. The lab will then test the soil for various nutrient levels, including magnesium and potassium.\n\nIn the meantime, you can also try inspecting the soil itself. If the soil is dry and cracked, it may be a sign that your plants are not getting enough water. Tomatoes need about 1-2 inches of water per week, either from rainfall or irrigation. If the soil is consistently dry, it may be causing the lower leaves to turn yellow.\n\nAnother thing you can try is to inspect the plant's growth pattern. If the lower leaves are turning yellow and the rest of the plant is healthy, it's possible that the plant is just getting a bit too big for its pot.",
